SIMPLE: hazard
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hazard
<hw>Haz"ard</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧z"⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>hasard</ets>, Sp. <ets>azar</ets> an unforeseen disaster or
accident, an unfortunate card or throw at dice, prob. fr. Ar.
<ets>zahr</ets>, <ets>z⟦amac⟧r</ets>, a die, which, with the article
<ets>al</ets> the, would give <ets>azzahr</ets>,
<ets>azz⟦amac⟧r</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A game of chance played
with dice.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The uncertain result of throwing a die; hence, a
fortuitous event; chance; accident; casualty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will stand the <qex>hazard</qex> of the die.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Risk; danger; peril; <as>as, he encountered the
enemy at the <ex>hazard</ex> of his reputation and life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men are led on from one stage of life to another in a condition of
the utmost <qex>hazard</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Billiards)</fld> <def>Holing a ball, whether the
object ball (winning <xex>hazard</xex>) or the player's ball (losing
<xex>hazard</xex>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Anything that is hazarded or risked, as the stakes
in gaming.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Your latter <xex>hazard</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>Any place into which the ball may
not be safely played, such as bunkers, furze, water, sand, or other kind
of bad ground.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hazard table</b></col>, <cd>a table on which hazard is
played, or any game of chance for stakes.</cd> -- <col><b>To run the
hazard</b></col>, <cd>to take the chance or risk.</cd> -- <col><b>to
hazard</b></col>, <cd>at risk; liable to suffer damage or
loss.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Danger; risk; chance. See
<er>Danger</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hazard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hazard
<hw>Haz"ard</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hazarded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hazarding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>hasarder</ets>.
See <er>Hazard</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To expose to the operation of chance; to put in
danger of loss or injury; to venture; to risk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men <qex>hazard</qex> nothing by a course of evangelical
obedience.</q> <rj><qau>John Clarke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>hazards</qex> his neck to the halter.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To venture to incur, or bring on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>hazarded</qex> the loss of whom I loved.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>hazard</qex> to cut their feet.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To venture; risk; jeopard; peril;
endanger.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hazard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hazard
<hw>Haz"ard</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧z"⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To
try the chance; to encounter risk or danger.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hazardable</ent>⟦br⟧
